The presentations of Siso of earth and water in a new exhibition
"People Swimming in the Swimming Pool" from the year 2022 is a work of art by Vicente Siso which will be exhibited starting on January 13th in the "Tierra del Sol" gallery (photo provided by Vicente Siso)
"Vicente Siso: Memories of the Land and Water" - this is the title of the exhibition at the new location of the "Tierra del Sol" gallery in West Hollywood. Siso has been part of the Studio Arts Program as an artist since 2012 and is now showing his first solo exhibition. Siso was born in Madrid in 1962 and grew up in Venezuela, Trinidad and Miami. At over twenty years old, he moved with his family to Southern California.
In numerous series of landscapes, portraits and still lifes in acrylic, pastel, charcoal or watercolor, Siso shows his masterful skills. Inspired by family portraits, his own reference photographs and memories, his colorful compositions prove the entire wide palette of his interests and his skills in different mediums. His tropical landscapes and parts of them show places from his past in detailed patterns. People are also integrated to create meaningful connections between culture, memory and nature. Siso titles his artworks with a mix of Spanish and English - a sign of the complexities of his life in Los Angeles County, so celebrated and important. The exhibition "Vicente Siso: Memories of the Land and Water" opens on Saturday, January 13 with a welcome from 6 to 8 pm. The exhibition will be shown until Sunday, March 3.
Gallery "Tierra del Sol", 7414 Santa Monica Blvd. Further information can be found at tierradelsolgallery.org.
Adapt the old, integrate the new and thus solve problems
At the district level, we only need to look at Sydney's Central Business District: an originally unpopulated area first transformed into a two-level city with a maximum height of 46 meters, and then into today's city with dizzying towers. To a much more limited extent, this can happen in Sydney's city centers and around transport hubs. Inner-city districts are also developing, with a trend towards affordable living spaces with buildings that are increasingly surpassed by forests in crucial areas. Naturally, this new living space that is being formed must be convincing in terms of design, and forests, landscape formation, and parks must also be included in addition to the essential infrastructure.
Our planning system must also adapt, so that the responsible persons in the district councils of the city centers, who have a rather critical position towards changes, do not alone have the competence to decide about the future development of their neighborhoods. One possibility could be to install an independent decision-making body that is committed to high-value concepts that are exclusively delivered under the tree canopy and consider space for families, large loggias and communal gardens - and visually the thing must also convince. This could be a lesson for the current NSW Government Architect. In this context, a carefully elaborated regulation must be considered.
Over the last 10 years, our lives have been transformed by technology. Many work from home, and Sydney has realised an impressive network of metros and trams. Online shopping has changed the way we do errands, and thanks to smartphones, friends and family can better maintain contact with each other. Precisely these adaptations, from one system to the next, are also possible in our architectural environment. The focus of planning in this sector must be on new adaptive use, instead of the preferred maintenance of traditional things.
Chris Johnson was the architect of the city of NSW from 1995 to 2005 and principal director of the NSW planning department from 2005 to 2009. From 2011 to 2019 he was CEO of the Urban Taskforce Australia.
A final intervention for women's equality
Last year, the World Economic Forum predicted that it would take five generations to achieve gender equality in every country. Now the World Bank wants to significantly shorten this time.
The international financial institution is in the process of introducing a strategy that should considerably promote the economic rights and opportunities for girls and women by 2030. The plan focuses on improving inclusion and resilience through access to finance, technical innovations, and changes in public directives and laws.
"The latest research has shown that both social norms and ways of thinking can change and that, for example, the involvement of men and young people can lead them to support gender equality," it says in a draft consultation of the plan. "Positive results in terms of equal rights can be accelerated and scaled if one better understands... how social norms and mentalities influence expectations, priorities, and daily practices."
Thoughts are difficult to quantify, in contrast to bank loans for women in the country or applications for girls' schools. And yet there are numerous indications that the integration of women can set a lot in motion. In Iran, women have become the biggest threat to the Islamic government in 40 years: They have refused to abide by the laws that force them to cover their hair. In some of the 130 countries with minimum quotas for the representation of women in government, for example in India, the resistance of men against the right to vote and the political activities of women has decreased.
In various villages in the African countryside, civil society organizations are replacing an extremely harmful initiation rite with health education. One of these programs helped Kamanda Timayio, a traditional leader from the Maasai Maparasha village in Kenya, to change his attitude towards female genital mutilation. He told the newspaper Le Monde that he had "overcome his ignorance" and that he would stop this practice.
The World Bank cites further examples: from 1970 to 2022, the literacy rate of women in Bangladesh quadrupled, and women's participation in earnings doubled. The country's gross domestic product is more than three times as high. The change has developed its own dynamic. The engagement of women as paid teachers and health workers in the villages themselves has created trust, and "has made the mobility and professional activity of women more socially acceptable".
The bank's plan targets norms and institutions where the generational change may not yet have been understood. In Rwanda, it took more than two decades for the country to establish itself as a model for land reforms that promoted the economic empowerment of women. "It doesn't help anyone if women are kept small," said Rwandan President Paul Kagame when he spoke in 2015 about land reform. "We must change the way we think, not just the laws."
The World Bank hopes to be able to disseminate this message.
Germanische Lokführer beunruhigen deutsche Unternehmer
In Germany, where employees and employers jointly manage many companies, large strikes are something unusual. There has practically never been a large wave of strikes. But for the moment, the "country of co-determination" is facing a week of strikes. In it, not only angry farmers block the roads with their tractors, but also railway employees will strike for three days. And as if that weren't enough, a doctors' strike is now also threatening, and already between Christmas and New Year, doctors' practices had closed their doors. This "mob of pitchforks," as some call it, will put the harmonious labor relations in Germany to the test at the beginning of the year.
The protests were apparently triggered by the government's decision to cut diesel subsidies for agriculture and to reduce tax breaks for agricultural motor vehicles. These measures were the last straw for the farmers. They also mobilised other disgruntled workers who are suffering from the burden of inflation, economic weakness and the austerity measures that the government has imposed on itself. On 9 January, German railway freight and passenger train drivers began a strike over working hours and wages.
To reduce tensions with the farmers, the government has declared itself ready for a phased reduction of the diesel subsidy over the next three years. The exemption from motor vehicle tax should also be maintained. The farmers have rejected these concessions as insufficient. On January 4, Economy Minister Robert Habeck wanted to leave a ship after returning from vacation with his family - a group of angry people protesting wanted to prevent him from doing so. If the locomotive drivers also show so little impression, it could become expensive for the German economy, judged the Institute for Economic Research IW in Cologne. The railway strike could cost the economy 100 million euros per day if production has to be interrupted. The automotive industry, the chemical and steel industries, Germany's largest economic sectors, are particularly dependent on rail freight traffic.
The atmosphere among the workers is becoming increasingly tense. "Calls with fantasies of revolution are circulating," Habeck warned. The far-right party "Alternative for Germany" is doing everything possible to provoke the protests. In Dresden, the "Freie Sachsen," another far-right party, infiltrated the farmers' protests and called for the "dissolution of the Ampel" (the German government).
Thomas Puls from the IW in Cologne fears that the protests could damage Germany's reputation as an economic hub. Local entrepreneurs already fear a German version of the yellow vest protests in France in 2018, which ended with demonstrators setting cars on fire on the Champs-Élysées and the police intervening with tear gas. Jochen Kopelke, the national president of the police union, warned in an interview with the Tagesspiegel: "The farmers' protests are probably just the beginning of a huge wave of protests that will come our way this year." Germany was the only one of the major economic regions with a decline in 2023, and the year ended with a particularly bitter note: an unexpected reduction in economic confidence in December. This year could become even more difficult.
The brewers are angry because of the decision of the winemakers regarding the regulations to avoid impurities.
In the EU debates on regulations to avoid waste, breweries argue that they are disadvantaged by the exceptions for winemakers regarding reuse quotas and deposit return systems. However, one of the leaders of the wine industry association believes that brewers "should mind their own business".
The European breweries admit that it is not fair and perhaps even against the law to allow exceptions from reuse quotas and such deposit return systems for wine but not for beer. Meanwhile, legislators are in the final round of discussions about a new law that should bring about a change in the ever-growing mountains of packaging waste.
The environment ministers have agreed before Christmas on a negotiating mandate from the Council of Europe regarding the proposed packaging and packaging waste regulation, thus clearing the way for further political discussions with the European Parliament, which are already taking place at a technical level.
"Our position is clear," wrote the European brewers' umbrella association, Brewers of Europe, to the members of the European Parliament and the leaders of the government negotiations (January 10). "If the goals and regulations of the packaging and packaging waste ordinance apply to beer, there is a legal obligation to apply it to all categories of alcoholic beverages."
At the supreme meeting of ministers on December 18, an exception was decided from the requirements for winegrowers, to have to offer 10% of the products in reusable containers in a reusable or refillable system by the end of the decade. By 2040, this quota should grow to 40%. This exception should also apply to the requirement that wine be excluded from the deposit refund system. This requirement is also supported by the European Parliament and should be introduced within the framework of the proposal by 2029.
The Czech and Belgian ministers promptly formulated their reservations at the supreme meeting on December 18 regarding the unequal treatment of beers, but they agreed. Belgium, which now holds the presidency of the EU Council and should be neutral in negotiations between governments, hopes that an agreement with parliament will be reached by the beginning of March.
Ignacio Sánchez Recarte, Secretary General of the European Wine Industry Association, the Comité Européen des Entreprises Vin, which represents approx. 7,000 winegrowers throughout Europe, rejects the reservations of beer producers. He told Euronews that a market dominated by multinational beer conglomerates cannot be compared with an industry that consists almost exclusively of small domestic producers.
More than 99% of the domestic wine industry consists of very small to medium-sized businesses, said Sánchez Recarte. He also questioned the value of the legal arguments presented by the breweries. In his opinion, his organization has focused on providing decision-makers with "relevant and adequate" information for its own industry.
"It is not my role to judge whether the beer industry should have this or that goal, as it depends on the concrete characteristic traits of their own industry," said Sánchez Recarte. "Therefore, brewers should take care of their own things and concentrate on their own obligations."
Brewers of Europe have shared a short legal analysis with Euronews, which was sent last year by the association to the European Commission. It argues that wine and beer are competing products, and that they are "at least partially mutually replaceable", and that rules that favor one industry over the other distort the market.
Simon Spillane, the chief operating officer of the lobby, said that brewers are "already at the forefront" with sustainable packaging. In this context, he drew attention to reusable bottles that are used around 165 times before being sorted and recycled. That they support reuse and recycling systems that are already introduced in many countries.
"That's why we advocate for an ambitious packaging and packaging waste ordinance. But we also need equal conditions in packaging legislation that treat beer and other alcoholic beverages according to the same rules. Every industry should contribute in the same way to achieving the goals and supporting the collection systems," said Spillane. "Any other approach means a competitive disadvantage for brewers."
The Biden administration lets economic criminals go.
Tim Whitehouse, ehemaliger Anwalt der U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) und Geschäftsführer von Public Employees for Environmental Responsibility, lobte die jüngsten Verbesserungen der Biden-Regierung bei der Umsetzung von Umweltfragen, räumte aber auch ein, dass solche Bemühungen auf grossen Widerstand stossen werden. "Es braucht eine zuverlässige Finanzierung und politische Unterstützung, um ein gutes Umsetzungsprogramm zu entwickeln", sagte er mir. "Die Instabilität im Kongress demoralisiert nicht nur die EPA-Mitarbeiter, sondern beeinträchtigt auch ihre Fähigkeit, strategisch und langfristig zu denken."
The problems of the EPA are not identical, but comparable to those of the Ministry of Justice. Its division for environment and natural resources, ENRD (Environment and Natural Resources Division) for short, deals with ecological crime. Uhlmann, who was deputy minister for implementation issues, was head of the ecological crime sector from 1990 to 2007, before he came to the EPA. The EPA sends its most serious civil and criminal cases to the ENRD, which, as an authority with relatively low finances, relies on others to decide which battles should be fought. In the 2022 fiscal year, the EPA forwarded fewer cases (88) to the Ministry of Justice than at any other time since 2000 and completed the fewest procedures since then. As stated in the draft for civil procedures, the EPA even under Trump completed an average of 94 civil procedures and forwarded 106 cases per year to the Ministry of Justice.
The general approach of the Ministry of Justice in cases of economic crime has been intensively examined by supporters. Observers have praised a few steps that the ministry has taken under Merrick Garland as Minister of Justice - such as, for example, the installation of a database for economic crime. However, Biden's Ministry of Justice has also strongly focused on the solution with principal losses. With this, companies can suspend or avoid criminal prosecution, and companies are encouraged to accuse individual employees to avoid extensive accusations. Kenneth Polite Jr., former Deputy Minister of Justice in the criminal division, has revised the division's implementation guidelines for companies to limit criminal prosecutions.
Die Debatte über den Shutdown verschärft den Konflikt unter den Republikanern.
Opponents of conservative spending in the House of Representatives today went against the party leadership and sank a series of votes. With this, they protested against the newest budget agreement of Speaker Mike Johnson with the Democrats, which, according to them, does not foresee enough cuts in the budget.
The Republican from Louisiana can still get out of the way on this issue, but on January 19th the deadline for the deliberation of four of the twelve budget plans for the year expires. Johnson has publicly declared that he will not support a transitional law, called "Continuing Resolution", to extend the deadline for these four draft laws until February 2nd, the deadline that applies to the other eight budget plans.
In view of the fact that this deadline is already in nine days, the leader of the Republican faction in the Senate, Mitch McConnell, announced that Congress must deliberate a "Continuing Resolution" to guarantee the continuation of the government's work. He thus threatens Johnson with breaking a promise with which he primarily wanted to calm the right wing of his party. Such a maneuver would probably have caused a lively ideological debate about the role of Republicans in spending cuts, which could result in a partial government shutdown or Johnson's dismissal.
The congressman Matt Rosendale from Montana told Newsweek: "I have clearly stated that the 'Continuing Resolution' is not the appropriate way to fund our government, because the Budget Act of 1974 foresees the deliberation of 12 appropriation bills. We have had plenty of time for that, and if the leadership does not instruct the committees to fulfill their duties and let the members of Congress vote on the matter, then that is the reason for the failure."
The Speaker of the House of Representatives, Mike Johnson, is confronted in the U.S. Capitol on December 12, 2023 in Washington, D.C. Johnson with a stubborn Republican faction that is unable to reach an agreement on the amount of spending in the budget. Photo: Kevin Dietsch/Getty Images
Rosendale, who is part of the far-right Freedom Caucus, was one of those who caused the vote to fail on Wednesday. For him, the total amount in Johnson's proposal is too high and he does not consider it sufficient to reduce the state's debt of 34 trillion dollars.
Rosendale was also one of the 71 Republicans who opposed the Fiscal Responsibility Act: the law negotiated between the Democrats and former Speaker Kevin McCarthy for fiscal responsibility, in which the basic conditions for Johnson's new negotiations with the leader of the Democrats in the Senate, Charles Schumer, had been fixed.
Even though Johnson had cancelled his agreement because it would have saved an estimated 16 billion dollars, the Freedom Caucus is of the opinion that he could have achieved even more. Moderate Republicans who had supported McCarthy's agreement judge this stance as unrealistic, which counteracts the Republicans' goal of forcing Congress to deliberate each of the twelve spending proposals separately and not to summarise them as a so-called omnibus procedure in a single vote as in recent years.
"Again, and the same idiotic behavior from some," Republican Representative Mike Lawler of New York told Newsweek. "Since there will be no mediation process, every bill must be treated and negotiated separately. Apparently, we will probably need more time for that. And I am not for a shutdown - so I also have no problem with a short-term 'Continuing Resolution' so that this process can be brought to an end."
This would be the first time since 1996 that Congress deliberates all twelve bills individually. According to Lawler, the delayed deliberation of the four bills is appropriate so that the process can proceed in an orderly manner. If Congress fails to deliberate the twelve bills by December, a one percent budget cut on discretionary spending in defense and non-defense sectors would be applied, according to the Fiscal Responsibility Act.
The Congressman Thomas Massie from Kentucky - one of the most fervent opponents of spending in the Republican party - was not among those who protested against the vote on Wednesday. However, he declared that a one-year "Continuing Resolution" with the consequence of a one percent cut in spending would be the best way to keep the government running and at the same time put an end to this constant desire to play with risk.
The path of greatest responsibility to achieve the reduction of expenses, however, is the approval of all twelve draft laws. Many Republicans, however, only hesitantly want to risk a shutdown and with it a reduction of one percent of defense spending. The urgency of deliberating the draft laws could cause a sufficient number of Republicans to ally with the Democrats to extend the deadline for the first four draft laws and to reach an agreement on the financing of the government's work, even if this would result in Johnson getting into a dispute with some hardliners from the right wing.
"It [the one percent cut] should serve as motivation and a means of pressure to pass the twelve draft laws separately," Massie explained to Newsweek. "I think we can first decide on a one-year 'Continuing Resolution', then exchange our arguments, and if we then face this small obstacle, I hope everyone will be motivated to act reasonably. I would do it that way."
Supervisory authority approves new Bitcoin ETF - a decisive term for cryptocurrencies
The American stock exchange supervisory authority, Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC), has reluctantly cleared the way for exchange-traded Bitcoin funds (ETFs). This is a long-awaited step by supporters of digital currencies, and criticized by financial observers who are skeptical of the cryptocurrency industry.
The authority has approved ten ETFs that invest in bitcoins, including funds from industry giants such as Blackrock and Fidelity, but also from smaller financial companies.
"The fact that we have today approved the listing on the stock exchange and the trading of certain bitcoin products traded on the stock exchange does not mean that we approve of and are in favor of Bitcoin," said SEC chief Gary Gensler in a statement. "Investors should continue to be cautious, given the numerous risks associated with bitcoins and products with values linked to cryptocurrencies."
He added that the approval of bitcoin funds does not mean that exchange-traded products (ETPs) based on other digital currencies or commodity values will be approved by the SEC.
"It is important that today's approval is limited to ETPs that contain a specific product that is not linked to a security, namely bitcoin. With this, we are not signaling any readiness to admit admission standards for crypto-assets. The approval also says nothing about the SEC's stance on the status of other crypto-assets under federal American securities law or about the situation of certain participants in the crypto-asset market not complying with federal securities laws," Gensler said.
Since then, similar fund proposals have been rejected by the SEC. Last year, however, the US Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia ruled that the SEC's refusal to approve Grayscale's application for the conversion of a derivatives fund was illegal. This fund should have been converted into a fund that would have invested directly in bitcoins. The court qualified the SEC's stance as "unfounded and arbitrary".
Gensler declared that he is of the opinion that the most solid path for the future is the approval of the listing and trading of these Spot-Bitcoin-ETP participation certificates, in view of these circumstances and those that are presented in more detail in the approval decision.
Die mit grosser Spannung erwartete Genehmigung wurde als entscheidender Moment für digitale Währungen gefeiert. Laut Befürwortern erweitert sie den Zugang zu Bitcoin-Investitionen und könnte zu einer breiteren Akzeptanz von Kryptowährungen als seriöse Finanzinvestition führen. Der Bitcoin-Preis ist in den letzten Monaten von ca. 25'000 auf über 45'000 Dollar explosionsartig gestiegen. Dies ist teilweise darauf zurückzuführen, dass viele Bitcoin-Investoren glauben, dass ETFs eine grössere Nachfrage nach dem Asset verursachen werden.
Opponents of the decision sharply criticized the SEC on Wednesday evening.
Dennis M. Kelleher, co-founder, president and CEO of Better Markets, announced that the approval is a "historic mistake". With it, crypto leaders are not only unleashed on tens of millions of investors and pensioners, but the stability of the financial markets will probably also be jeopardized."
Kelleher further stated: "The unregulated crypto industry has clearly reached its absolute lowest point, due to a flurry of arrests, criminal convictions, insolvencies, lawsuits, scandals, massive losses, and millions of victims among investors and clients. Who would have thought that it would receive help from the SEC, by approving a proven and well-known form of investment. Thus, the SEC has enabled the mass commercialization of a financial product known to be worthless, volatile, and prone to defrauding American neighbors."
Increase of 30% in complaints due to the use of the Russian language in Ukraine - RT Russia and former Soviet Union
To pacify the country, the population is intimidated into making denunciations.
The number of denunciations to the Ukrainian authorities against people who speak Russian increased by 30% last year. The authorities in Kyiv actively encourage the population to report corresponding cases, as they say, to "protect" the country from Russian influence.
According to information from the Commissioner for the Protection of the National Language, 3,692 violations of the language law were reported in 2023. Kyiv, Kharkiv and Odesa "still have the highest number of reports of violations. Therefore, it should be one of the priorities of the responsible municipalities this year to strictly ensure that the language rights of residents are respected in all areas of public life," said Taras Kremin, the language ombudsman in Ukraine.
Kremen also confirmed that a taxi driver who had spoken Russian with his clients was fined 3,400 Hryvnia (89 dollars). The mediator drew the public's attention to the fact that there is "a detailed algorithm of measures if information or services are to be shared in the national language". He appealed to the population to immediately submit complaints in such cases on the commissioner's website.
In 2019, Ukraine passed a law that obliges the use of the Ukrainian language in all sectors of public life, including government, medicine, science, education, and media. Violations are subject to fines. Since the beginning of the military conflict with Russia in 2022, Ukraine has been conducting a campaign for complete derussification, which, according to parliamentarians, is necessary to protect against Russian influence. Local authorities have completely banned artworks, performances, books, films, songs, and instruction in the Russian language in schools and universities, and recommended that schoolchildren speak Ukrainian among themselves even during breaks.
Last year, a young musician was briefly arrested and forced to apologize with a video message after he had sung songs by the Soviet singer-songwriter Viktor Tsoi on the streets of Lviv. The dismissal of several teachers who had spoken Russian with their students also caused strong public reactions.
The secretary of the National Security and Defense Council of Ukraine, Oleksiy Danilov, had previously declared that the Russian language must disappear from Ukrainian territory, because it is "an element of enemy propaganda and a brainwashing of the population".
Moscow is of the opinion that these laws violate the rights of the Russian-speaking population, which makes up about half of Ukraine's population. The spokeswoman for the Russian Foreign Ministry, Maria Zakharova, declared in February that Kyiv's "discriminatory campaign" against the language is becoming increasingly "scandalous." In a survey by the Institute for Sociology in Kyiv in September of last year, 45% of the respondents indicated linguistic discrimination as the most frequent type of prejudice in Ukraine.
Celeste is my dearest "little, good commercial freeware game, sometimes also funny from afar, with wonderfully detailed graphics" in the arch of corruption, because in the original version the Double Dash is a Power-Up without a red thread in a treasure chest, and in the commercial game it brings tears to my eyes.
In general, I really like the combination of the two games. The advantage of short stories is that you can "jump to the good part". This can have more tension and give more satisfaction. With long stories, the advantage is that you can give a much greater emotional weight to the elements of the action. Of course, not much happens all the time, but in return, you also get more.
The culmination of Celeste, the commercial game, is actually just the Pico-8-Game and that is puffed up from a mechanical and narrative point of view with many hours, which makes it even much more difficult. Celeste is so proud of its little Parent Game, that it has always introduced allusions, such as the monument, the development of "2000M ... 2500M ...", the Power-Up, the banner above. You can play the original game directly on the start screen.
Celeste is neither "the good version" nor "the finished version" of Pico-8, but just another version of the same main story. For someone who likes both short and long stories, it is really interesting and great to see how the connections have been made so obviously.
It would have been possible to develop another medium-length variant, between the two variants, which tells the same extended story that works, but with a shorter duration and fewer absurd production values. I think that would have been my preferred variant, so to speak, as an arc of emotional tension. Instead, the main arc of tension for individual players in the commercial game is only a small part of the whole. It is primarily intended to be a large playground for the world's most popular platform physics, which is still fine in my opinion.
