Up until now, I have only had a full anaesthetic for one operation. It was a "small" neurosurgical intervention to make more space for my brain, because I was born with a deformity that caused symptoms after the birth of my children (Chiari Malformation). The moment I woke up, I have never forgotten it, and I relive it a little every time I watch medical shows, especially if a neurosurgeon is present :-). I've had the Hospital playlist on my list for a long time, and I really like it at the moment. #karma
My surgeon really thinks of everything. He called me the day before, because it was going to snow, and when the treatment team took care of me, when I woke up from the anesthesia in the recovery room, my surgeon noticed that I had opened my eyes and that the bandage was in front of my eyes. I mean, all that besides the operation. But it was still irritating. It was one of the most horrible things I've ever done. I slept and it was all over.
I had my period, but I had to take it off. That's why they gave me that mesh underwear that you wear after the diaper. But in the operating room, you are completely undressed and covered with a sheet. Sometime before waking up, a kind nurse changed my underwear. Except for the diapers when I was awake and got help, or as a baby, no one has ever done anything so private for me. That was also my only time in intensive care. I had to go to intensive care because of the type of operation.
Because of my operation I had to rest a lot, so I watched seasons 1-3 of Grey's Anatomy. That McDreamy was a neurosurgeon helped. I observed how the patient was positioned, so that I could imagine what would happen to me. Since my operation in 2018, there has been more neurosurgery in the Hospital Playlist than in all other medical shows, since I watched Grey's. How nice that there is art and entertainment to give meaning to our lives.
Thanks to the Hospital Playlist I could transplant a kidney.
Wow!
I often wonder if millennials were the last generation who could develop a relationship with artists without being expected to also view them critically.
We grew up in a golden age of media with a collective memory for pop culture that no longer exists.
We were able to rush into things, without having to consider where they came from, because it was not at all simple to ascertain that.
We didn't have to question the position where we put them. These parasocial relationships were so important and influenced our lives.
Why do we have such a strong tendency towards nostalgia?
When "The Office" was still on, my friends and I used to order pizza and watch the show together every Thursday.
That was completely different from today with streaming, where 12 episodes come out at once and everyone watches when they feel like it and puts "spoiler warnings" on posts in social media and discusses it in closed groups.
The subconscious longs for that universal community that once dominated everything.
Why do so many of us still watch silly series like "The Office" or films like "Anchorman", which have so many one-liners that would be memes today.
We have done all this and thought that most people understand it.
Today we can no longer start from the fact that everyone knows something, even if it spreads virally in a massive way.
It gives us a lot, a lot, and it gives us no possibility to organize all that. Who knows if we will ever get out of this overload again?
We are prisoners in a vicious circle of constantly discovering new content, only to then realize that the artist is broke or that he is a hypocrite.
Therefore we must hold on tightly to our nostalgia and at the same time accept that the people who created the works we liked can also have great flaws.
In parasocial relationships among us with greater caution.
To us it is clear that it is difficult to become rich and powerful without stepping on someone's toes one way or another on that path.
Since we have lost our collective consciousness in connection with media, we have developed a class consciousness that promotes our critical thinking.
There are still always those among us who put someone on a pedestal, only to then be shocked when that person falls down.
We are in a phase of change and I am just wondering where this will end.
