It's an absolute niche problem, but if you want to build/customize small robot figures, it really gets on your nerves that you HAVE to build something that is made for war and for killing.
So during the first decade of the 21st century. Then there were Bionicles. These were adventurers/heroes with completely elemental powers and with different personalities and hobbies and so on, but before and after that there was only something like Warhammer, Gundam, Battletech, where it's always about being a weapon that is paraded in the accompanying media in a completely useless way.
It's clear, those other sources SAY that "war is something bad", but then they sell themselves as figures and merchandise machines that kill. What should we do then?
I think the solution is to separate between their appearance and this fictitious use, as is also done in the real world with tanks and jets, but my brain has great DIFFICULTIES doing that.
Because the figures already have a cool look, and I like how they are built and how their design reflects certain character qualities, but then it says with every set: "By the way, here is your laser sword and your (at least one) pistol!"
For the most part, this is probably because boys' toys have always had something to do with violence, such as GI Joe and Transformers, but seriously, we are in the present.
I'm already looking forward to seeing Berry's pacifist robot family, made with a 3D printer ;)
