An anarchist declares, to whom it doesn't matter a damn to keep his identity secret, gives his DNA to a biotechnology company, to receive a dubious overview of his "ancestry". What could possibly go wrong here?
My wife wanted this as a starting point. Without going too deep, but she believes that a couple of her so-called ancestors are not really her ancestors. I would like to support her and see the effect of genetic derivations by means of a small control sample. We know a lot about our family.
Perhaps there was someone unfaithful in my family, but if one considers the largely poor roots of my family, all the affairs probably happened in villages, in small, more or less homogeneous towns and in ethnic ghettos, lol.
My grandmother left her husband for his brother and I have a second cousin on the other side of my family who left his wife for her aunt. My family might wander around for this, but it doesn't get very far.
And now my wife has a bad mood, because my "extraction" went much faster than expected. That bothers me, maybe her genome shouldn't make so many ceremonies.
The results are here and - drumroll, please - they correspond completely to my family history. 89.9% British and Irish, the large part of which is concentrated on the Scottish Borders region, on the west part of Ireland, on Wales and on Cornwall. There isn't much Breton, however, perhaps because it's either so close to Cornwall that it can't be distinguished in my case, or because the Breton part of my family doesn't come from there.
Since I was around 40 years old, I had worried a bit that there might be children I knew nothing about. So far, only one of my cousins has abandoned his children (perhaps).
Fuck, King Louis XIV, one of your ancestors is an anarchist!
