As an academic, one has little time for recreation, but during the time one sits at the desk, the best thoughts come.
Even if it takes more effort to publish more, it doesn't always lead to better results. One shouldn't shy away from recreating oneself if one wants to become a better scientist.
So I'm charging my batteries again:
Always use both halves of the brain.
As scientists, we usually use the analytical part of our brain. But if I also use the creative part of my brain (e.g. by playing guitar, painting, etc.) I feel as if I have increased my mental capacities. Through this I become better in both sectors.
Train the muscles, not just the head.
Sport is not just something for adventurous triathletes or for people who want to look good. Sport also improves the quality of life. Thoughts, atmosphere, productivity - everything is connected. Taking a break once and getting away from the desk makes the time at the desk more productive again.
The permission to leave.
Charging the batteries again does not always mean that new habits have to be developed. A good film or a good book can have at least as much effect as creative work and physical activities. It is important to be clear that it is okay to relax and do nothing. There is no room for feelings of guilt!
Among these things I have noticed that they help me to recreate myself. But there are also many others. What is not done to enthuse oneself further for science and not to get a burnout?
