Ok, I've hung up a new nesting box. It looks like this in its new place in the garden.
But let's look back a bit. Nobody asks: "What is really in here?"
Above is one of those ESP32 camera boards with a camera with a Fisheye lens and an IR-LED that I have from a Raspberry Pi camera.
The reason for the curious shape of this plastic box is the movable side wall of the litter box. I bought it like that and couldn't change it, so I had to build everything around it.
Since there is no electricity in the garden, the entire installation is powered by a solar panel and a 2600mAh 18650 cell.
I didn't photograph the charger or the cell, but here is a picture of the panel.
In the grey box that hangs on the side of the gearbox is the battery.
If it is charged, I have a battery life of about 4 hours.
That is now really a feature. So the birds also get a bit of privacy.
At first I wasn't sure if the internet in our garden would be enough for this construction. The old access points that I replaced last autumn would not have been enough.
But the new ones are enough for this sector.
It's been a while since I intended to install a TP-Link CPE210 on the roof and point it into the garden.
Perhaps I'll still do that when I install additional nest boxes with cameras. I'll probably use that especially in places that are further away from the house.
Now the camera is offline and I don't know why. It turned off just an hour after sunset.
It is possible that the battery had not charged three hours before sunset, because there was not enough light.
A little less than half a day was too little to fully charge the battery.
I'll wait and see what happens tomorrow.
I don't have any telemetry for the battery. Perhaps I will have to change that in the future.
