The development of humanity progresses continuously. Even in difficult times, we develop and adapt. In the cities, there is still great prosperity, and technological progress is becoming ever faster. With the discovery of Ignniat recently, humanity has been catapulted to maximum heights, but the greatest thing still awaits us. This newly acquired knowledge that humanity has gained here can only be valued as a divine effect, and the Gods will rejoice at our presence in heaven. The company Karascene has had Ignniat examined intensively and values the potential of this mineral very highly. And don't worry: according to examinations, no side effects or problems are to be expected with the exploitation of Ignniat. This mineral is destined for something greater.
14 January 2542, 10:26 PM
A click. The same stream was repeated again: the day the world was devastated. My father always got angry if he saw that I couldn't take my eyes off it. His sad face made my stomach clench. I always feel bad when this stream plays, because it awakens so many memories, but none of them very good. With a sigh, I get up to get other thoughts. I always try to cheer him up, to chase away the bad mood by at least making him a little happy. But today I'm tired.
I approach the door quietly and call to my father: "I'm going out for a bit, dinner is in the fridge." No answer. Why bother. Usually he hears me, he'll come down by himself when he's cold. I close the door quietly and sigh once more, after the lock is completely closed. I almost forgot to put my hand on the cold metal scanner to lock the door. If anything was special about this apartment, it was its equipment with modern technology, which most buildings had anyway. For a long time, no other technology had been used.
On this cold, rainy night, I finally took my exploration walk through Paltricus - a privilege reserved for those who had escaped the mutation through flight or sheer luck. The night was illuminated by splendid stars that were already many thousands of years old. It must be lonely in the universe. Paltricus was a beautiful city, but there one felt more like in a cage and not like in a luxurious home. The city was crammed with apartments, houses, and other residential buildings, most of which had several hundred floors, thanks to Ignniat. This mineral had proven to be a stroke of luck for technology and architecture and had expanded our living base. The public, however, knows very little about this mineral. Mainly because it is kept under strict secrecy.
To free myself from the disturbing thoughts, I set off to drink a coffee in my favourite place. Most people avoid it because of a rumour that a werewolf is roaming the surrounding region. That's what those who have been infected with the virus are called. That has never worried me - I've had enormous luck in my life - and the owner is a great guy. Who would want to give up a free coffee in exchange for a late-night chat?
When I entered, a strong ringing sound startled my discomfort and the smell of fresh coffee animated my nose. Anton, the owner of the place, was as always behind the counter. The place was practically empty, with the exception of a couple of people in the back. After the long walk, I approached the counter, let myself fall onto one of the stools and sighed. I see Anton and he brings me the usual. "Hello Lillith, long night?" his rough voice echoed in the coils of my brain. "More or less," I replied exhausted and became more tired second by second.
To chase away my boredom, I take a few small sips of my coffee in front of me. "Are things still going so badly since the story with the envelope...?" I spoke softly so as not to scare away the last guests from Anton's place. He nodded while wiping a glass with a cloth. This place is actually a bar, but I've never come here to drink. Behind me, there was a murmur, but the conversation with Anton was rather short tonight. With a short wave of the hand and a bit more energy than before, I left the place.
That wasn't the best idea to walk late at night through the dark streets. But still better than staying in this stuffy apartment listening to the Swiss German sex. You heard them more often than your own music. With a short sigh, I looked back at the road in front of me. I'm probably going to Al's shop, the baker, to pass the time looking for interesting junk. When I heard footsteps nearby behind me, I regretted my decision. Maybe I'm worrying too much, but in this region you only went if you wanted to be robbed or stabbed. The region was known for the mafia and gang crime...
Funny, isn't it? Only half of humanity was left, and yet we never stopped hitting each other's heads. I ran faster, the pawn shop was right around the corner, and I was sure of it. When I was in front of a lit sign with the inscription "Alborn Pawn Shop," a quick glance back over my shoulders confirmed that I was no longer being pursued. With quieter steps, I entered the shop. This shop was rather off the radar, because Alborn often took in mutants who were in Paltricus without permission. The shop was dark and curious, Al wasn't even there. No fugitives. Nothing. Something couldn't be right here.
Cautiously I went to the back room of the shop, where a low murmur and conversation could be heard, behind a metal grate that could be removed with the hands. I crawled into the ventilation shaft - for the moment the simplest and safest method. When I pushed myself through, I heard conversations between men in strange clothes. Then I saw Al in chains. It was clear that they would catch him eventually.
I really wanted to go to Alborn, but that was too big a number for me. I really had no business sticking my nose into other people's affairs, especially not if they were just arguing with the strong power of the state. And yet I couldn't do anything else. With a light sigh, I gently pulled the cat out of its fixation from under me and let myself down into the quiet room. "Psst. Al, Al!" I whispered, and when he didn't answer, I got louder. "Lilith? What are you doing here? You have to go, otherwise they'll catch you."
"Just say...", I said softly to myself. While we were trying to free the chains around his arms, voices approached and the loud footsteps became louder and louder. "Quick! Crawl back into the barrel and disappear. In any case, don't come back. If we see each other again, then not in this city." He spoke quickly and the panic in his eyes didn't exactly help to calm me down. I followed his advice. I couldn't stay any longer. Damn it, Al. After I had left the ventilation shaft, I ran away. It hurt to lose such a loyal friend. Al was taking me to the ...... other city? So many things were going through my head. I was so angry, but also sad. I had intensively dealt with the outer cities and with the capital of the infected. It was called Alcatraz, after the prison of the same name. The name fit well with what I had read about it. Not to mention that the non-mutants had cut off all remaining land connections with the infected regions. A tragic story.
A penetrating quietness surrounded me on the way home. The thoughts in my head were swirling and I was almost bursting that I hadn't been able to help Al. When I finally arrived home after this terrible walk, I was in tears, and the thunder from the clouds above me could frighten and annoy anyone. My father was already asleep on the sofa. A rerun of an old film from about 10-12 years ago was playing. Sighing, I went into my room. I let myself fall onto the bed. I was almost no longer able to keep my eyes open and fell asleep almost immediately.
EXPLOSION
January 19, 2543, 2:34 PM
Time passed very quickly. A few days ago Alborn had been taken away. I didn't know where. Only that they had taken him somewhere. The men's clothes seemed familiar to me, but I simply couldn't remember where from. With a sigh, I placed my hands on the system in front of me that glowed red and purple - it would have been simple for me to hack it. I doubt they had secured it additionally... But it would be better not to do that. But of course I put aside my moral reservations. My fingers moved as if tele-guided over the keyboard and opened several monitors. Oh, how good I am! I was very well known on different websites, I was called "GHOST" there. A very striking name. I have to admit that I use the name S3IE4T on every website, but the thought that it was given to me by others pleases me.
I downloaded the surveillance camera footage to my mobile device and watched each one very carefully. Nothing. As if they had never been there. That makes no sense. The cameras are well secured, even against external access. How...? DAMN IT. I had been screaming to chase the thoughts out of my head. I went to the door, put on my shoes and grabbed my keys. "I'll be gone for a moment, Dad." Silence. That's normal, he never answers. He was probably once again busy with something more important than me.
When I left the apartment, it shook me briefly and a shiver ran down my spine. Alone. I ignored the feeling and forced myself to go to the pawn shop to do some research. But my legs carried me to Anton's small bar. It was really quiet there and I really needed someone to talk to. Who would have been more suitable than a bartender from whom you have something good.
It was unusually full, full of people I had never seen before. Anton always worked alone and was very stressed, certainly because of the large number of guests. "I'd like a coffee." I deliberately spoke in a low voice to annoy him a little. He turned around briefly and I had to laugh softly when I saw his upper lip on his face. "Come on Lilith, don't make me jump like that..." he said softly in a tired voice. "It seems you have a lot to do... Should I help you? Something's going on here." I didn't really want to serve these annoying people, but I felt sorry for Anton because he had to cope with this crowd all alone. "Would you do that? You'll get your money later..." he mumbled and looked at me with his dog's eyes. War tactics for advances...
After having changed my clothes into a kind of work uniform, I helped Anton at the bar. Despite the constant attempts at flirting and approaching me, which didn't really bother me, to tell the truth, the work went quite well. I will talk to Anton after my shift. I have to get Al out of my head, even though I know I will do further research in his pawn shop after my work in the bar, but still...
Flames shoot out of Thassalin's throat, as the enormous Thraki has set fire to a certain piece of wood and then swooped over it to see movements. Curiously, he screamed behind me when he slowed down. Thassalin had forgotten the passengers on his shoulders.
"What are you doing, Tenuk, you have already transformed into a Thracian once!"
"If I wanted to, that would be something completely different than being pulled up by a huge pink dragon!"
"It wasn't that easy, was it, Kayel?"
Kayel was obviously not of Nyssi's opinion. He seemed less black than usual and his claws had dug so deep into Thassalin's arms that the Thracian was bleeding. But that didn't seem to bother Thassalin. Nevertheless, it had become clear to him that he had scared his new friends and he sat down on a clearing.
"I'M SORRY, BUT I HAD TASTED SOMETHING. AND I HAD TO TAKE CARE OF THAT!"
"But did you have to bring us with you too?", grumbled Tenuk, as he climbed down from Thassalin's antlers and slid down his tail. "And we left Retvik behind! We left our great and strong warrior alone! How is he ever going to get back to us?"
"He certainly has an idea..." Nyssi grumbled. "Retvik isn't the fastest, but he isn't stupid."
"Yes, but is Retvik also in the vehicle?"
He nodded and turned back towards Tenuk. "Of course he knows how to go."
"Have you ever seen Reto drive a vehicle? He doesn't have a truck like you, and I've never seen him drive a small car like Kayel's. Besides, he only started taking the car to work because you always take us with you. He only has his bike."
A slap interrupted them. To Thassalin something seemed very funny, but nobody knew what he was laughing at. It took a while until Thassalin had calmed down.
"I'M SORRY, BUT I HAD IMAGINED YOUR GIANT FRIEND ON SUCH A SMALL CHILD'S BIKE. THAT WAS HILARIOUS! I WISH I HAD THAT KIND OF TELEPATHY. A GRAND IMAGINATION! ONE I CAN'T SHARE!"
Kayel sighed, because he could imagine what was happening right in Thassalin's head. "Yes, that's true. But what did you know, and why did you leave so suddenly?"
He flew away, disappeared and vanished. When he returned after a short time, he threw something lifeless at Nyssi's feet. It was an Orothrak, a very rare golden-white dragon creature. But it was missing its head. "ANOTHER DEAD ONE. I HEAR THEIR SCREAMS. TASTE THEIR BLOOD. SOMETHING IS FORCING ME TO PROTECT AND HUNT. AS YISINI COMMANDS. THEY ARE VERY CLOSE."
The big Thraki was suddenly gone. Nyssi and Kayel were also gone and looked attentively towards a clearing in the glade. Something big and black stared at them and snorted. Whatever it was, it flapped two enormous wings and flew directly towards Thassalin, without paying attention to the three smaller creatures among them. Kayel and Tenuk just managed to protect themselves, but Nyssi was dragged away and almost thrown onto Thassalin.
The dragon reacted to this attack by snapping at Nyssi and lashing the slave with its enormously long and agile tail on his limbs, before rising into the air itself. The black creature with double wings pursued them with great speed.
Kayel had two slugs in his hand while he took his rifle from the hook and opened a bag that contained an ammunition belt. He hung the belt over his chest, but quickly noticed that Nyssi, the Thraki and the monster were out of sight.
"Hey, Tenuk, if you could transform into something that can fly?", Kayel asked.
"Whom would you like to prosecute?"
"Clear!"
"But... one of them is a gigantic monster!"
"And then? I'm here with a high-quality rifle in my hand and could just shoot right away. But, now, how should I say it - I would have to see him to be able to shoot him."
Tenuk hesitated, then he moved forward to get more space. With a painful groan and only quietly, Tenuk's body tensed, his fur transformed into scales and his arms into wings. He quickly transformed into a normal light blue Thraki, but his eyes remained red.
"Come up."
As a normal Thracian, Tenuk now had a real shield of scales that ran along his arms. And practically, a few spines had also grown on his arms, where Kayel could hold on. It took a little too long for Tenuk to get started, but once he was in the air, he quickly oriented himself and tried to begin the pursuit.
Tenuk and Kayel quickly noticed that they were not alone. Another black creature quickly appeared below them, and Tenuk barely managed to avoid a collision.
"Would that be the other gigantic monster that causes fear, the one Lanex was afraid of?" Kayel frowned. He tried to shoot the second beast, but missed and quickly reloaded the rifle.
Tenuk did not answer. He was too busy concentrating on the flight towards Nyssi and Thassalin, even though the other beast was chasing them. Kayel turned from the rudder to keep an eye on the monster. That it was chasing them was an advantage for Kayel because that way he could aim and shoot better. Two shots went through the beast's wings. It screamed in pain and lowered itself under the bushes. Kayel was not sure if it was still following him, but it was certainly no longer able to catch up with them.
A good distance in front of them, Nyssi held her ground, while Thassalin swung his arms and spat flames at the black monster. The creature was definitely wounded. It seemed to be terribly angry, but not ready to give up. The fireballs did not seem to have the desired effect. When Thassalin stretched out, Nyssi took the opportunity to take her own weapon, a good old rifle, in hand. It was certainly nothing special, not a first choice, but perhaps the bullets could scare the black beast.
No, apparently not. The creature just puffed and tried to fly directly towards Thassalin. Fortunately, Thassalin, despite his size, was agile enough and dodged, but Nyssi let out a scream when she lost her grip on Thassalin's smooth scales.
"WHERE ARE THE SAUSAGES?" Nyssi shouted.
"LOOK AT THAT THING!"
"THAT'S BECOMING DIFFICULT!"
Thassalin whistled and flew in a circle, closer to that mountain that he called his home. The dark beast followed him, but got into a slight panic when a ray of fire touched it from behind. It hadn't noticed that it was no longer alone. It got even more panicked when Thassalin slowed down and then whipped his tail against its head and thus diverted it from its course.
Bruntuland, puffing and blowing, flew up and spat into the air. Everything immediately became dark, as if the monster were sucking the light out of the sky and replacing it with a cloud of eternal night.
When he was no longer able to see anything all at once, Thassalin tried to retreat. He felt how he brushed the treetops before finally falling into a clearing. The beast seemed to know exactly where he had fallen, and flew directly towards him and pulled the black cloud with it.
"Kayel!", Tenuk shouted when he had slipped out of the cloud and had begun to fly in circles to search for Nyssi and Thassalin in the darkness below. "What should we do now? Kayel...? Kayel, where are you?"
Below, Nyssi got to her feet with difficulty. She was sure she had broken something, but her curious supernatural healing powers were already beginning to take effect. Unfortunately, this was not true for Thassalin. He had dragged himself exhausted to the only tree that was not broken under his weight. Nyssi made every effort to get close to Thassalin, but she could barely see two meters. Everything was completely dark and full of deep shadows. And in these shadows something was screaming and rattling.
A terrible armed tail was shattered near Nyssi on the ground and thrown around. However, she noticed that the tail only made wild movements and did not try to move it precisely. The beast, or what little Nyssi could see and hear of it, grumbled and clawed at the shadow it had created. Something shot like an arrow through the darkness and pierced and irritated the monster.
All at once he fired a shot through the forehead, and the monster became quiet, fell to the ground and remained there without moving. The darkness around them dissolved and they saw what had happened: Kayel was standing on the beast, holding his smoking rifle.
"That was certainly... the leap of a shadow, the most foolish I've ever made... Thanto kat'olon...", Kayel tried to catch his breath again. His eyes glowed almost black and a dark energy swirled around his body. But as he spoke, the color returned to his armor, and his eyes regained their normal yellow color.
This lasted a moment until Nyssi understood what had happened. They all knew that Kayle had these curious shadow powers. He only used them rarely, because most considered them strange and frightening. But Nyssi didn't know that Kayle could use these powers even in any kind of darkness. And as Kayle behaved, he himself was quite surprised.
"Are you okay?", Nyssi quickly asked.
"Yes, I'm fine. I've killed something, I'll be in order again soon." Kayel contemplated his work, while Tenuk flew down from above, settled beside him and regained his normal form of Spast.
Now that the beast no longer moved, they could see better what it was. Its fur was very black and slimy, but the slime remained firmly attached to its body. It had four wings and four limbs that all ended in long, sharp claws, and two horns protruded from its head.
Before Tenul and Kayel could ask what they had in front of them, which the devil brought, something screamed and jumped out of a bush nearby. However, it did not reach them because a familiar vehicle crashed into its side and caused the monster to stop, sliding, at Nyssi's feet. Nyssi didn't want to risk anything. She grabbed the rifle and shot without thinking at its head, and the creature died on the spot.
"Oops...", Retvik mumbled from the driver's seat, before he switched off the engine of the monster and got out of the truck. "Uhm, that wasn't really my intention. Is everything alright with you?"
"You missed the whole action," Tenuk complained. "Where were you?"
"You just left me alone. I came as fast as possible..." Retvik sighed. "May I ask what terrible beasts those are?"
Retvik's question was fortunately answered by Thassalin, who was back on his feet. He was full of cuts and scratches and a little dazed, but he was not seriously injured.
"YOU HAVE KILLED THE CORRUPTED! THE INFECTIOUS MONSTERS. CREATURES THAT HAVE GONE AWAY FROM HERE WHEN CORRUPTION HAS ATTACKED YOUR GODS."
"You managed the terrible creature, the monstrous goddess that we ... helped to kill?", Tenuk stammered.
"YES. EXACTLY THAT ONE. PERHAPS EVEN MORE. BUT I COULDN'T SHOOT IT IN THE HEAD. I DON'T HAVE ANY FIREARM. AND TWO AGAINST ONE IS FAIR, ISN'T IT?" Thassalin limped over to Kayel and stroked his head. "THANK YOU VERY MUCH, MY LITTLE ONE. YOU REMIND ME OF MY OLD FRIEND ARKADIN. JUST NOT SO INFERNAL AND NOT SO CAPABLE OF KILLING ENTIRE UNIVERSES."
"Ehm … thanks … I think so …" Kayel said from his shoulders. "So are we done here now?"
Nyssi used the needles. She took her camera and took a few photos of the animals that were now definitely dead. Then she drew her favorite weapon, the dagger adorned with the god of death, and began to scrape off one of the animal's horns. Then she moved on to the second. But as soon as Nyssi had finished, the animals went up in flames and transformed into a pile of ashes within seconds. The same thing happened to the horns that Nyssi had cut off.
"This is now practical and impractical at the same time...", Nyssi sighed. "But now at least I have the photos, hopefully."
